sured by fractions of millimeters. This light is never truly in focus, whic=
h is why size of the circle of confusion is used to determine the quality o=
f a <a href=3D"https://www.studiobinder.com/blog/different-types-camera-len=
ses-explained/" target=3D"_self" data-wpel-link=3D"advanced" rel=3D"" title=
=3D"">lens</a>. The smallest circle a lens can generate (circle of least co=
nfusion) registers a light source in =E2=80=9Cperfect focus.=E2=80=9D&nbsp;=
</p><p>This is used to measure lens precision. Once you=E2=80=99ve calculat=
ed the circle of confusion, you can then accurately determine how precise t=
he focus of your lens will be, and paired with the <a href=3D"https://www.s=
tudiobinder.com/blog/focal-length-camera-lenses-explained/" target=3D"_blan=
k" class=3D"" style=3D"outline: none;">focal length</a>, you can determine =
the hyperfocal distance of a particular lens.&nbsp;</p></div><div class=3D"=
